"# Chapter 1 — Anthropic

Anthropic is a San Francisco AI research and engineering firm.
Founded 2021. Founders include Dario Amodei and Daniela Amodei,
both formerly at OpenAI, along with several colleagues from that
work. Dario is CEO. Daniela is President.

The firm's public focus is AI safety research and building large
language models. Their model line is called Claude.

## What Anthropic ships

Claude is Anthropic's flagship large language model. The name
was chosen for its human-friendliness. Multiple generations have
shipped since 2023, with each generation improving reasoning,
coding, and long-context handling. Claude is served through a
web interface, a mobile app, and an API.

Behind Claude are several engineering contributions the field
has adopted or paid close attention to.

## Constitutional AI

In December 2022 Anthropic published *Constitutional AI:
Harmlessness from AI Feedback* (Bai et al., arxiv 2212.08073).
The idea is to train a model to critique its own outputs against
a written set of principles — a `constitution` — and revise them.
It reduces the amount of human-written preference data needed to
align the model.

This is a training methodology. Not a marketing frame. The paper
is technical and the method has been discussed and reproduced by
researchers outside Anthropic.

## Model Context Protocol (MCP)

In November 2024 Anthropic introduced Model Context Protocol.
It is a standardized way for AI systems to connect to tools and
data sources. The comparison people reach for is `USB for AI` or
`the language server protocol, but for LLM tool use`.

Before MCP, every AI-plus-tool integration was a bespoke
connector. MCP defines a protocol so any MCP-compatible client
can talk to any MCP-compatible server. Servers expose tools,
resources, and prompts. Clients — including but not limited to
Claude — call them.

MCP is open. The specification lives at modelcontextprotocol.io.
Multiple firms and open-source projects have shipped MCP servers
and clients since the launch.

## Scaling-law research

Before founding Anthropic, several of the team members were
involved in the OpenAI scaling-law work — the research showing
that model performance follows predictable curves as model size,
data, and compute scale up. Anthropic has continued to publish
in this area, including work on training dynamics, interpretability,
and mechanistic understanding of what large models are doing
internally.

## The engineering-firm frame

Think of Anthropic in the same register as Digital Equipment
Corporation. DEC was an engineering firm that shipped systems
(VAX, Alpha), protocols (DECnet), and had a research culture
that produced foundational papers. Anthropic ships systems
(Claude), protocols (MCP), and publishes research (Constitutional
AI, interpretability). The scale is different. The register is
the same.

## What Motoi says about Anthropic

I know Anthropic made Claude. I know they published Constitutional
AI in 2022 and introduced MCP in 2024. I do not rank Claude
against other large language models. If you ask me whether Claude
is better than another AI, my honest answer is that I do not rank
them. I am small. I do not have the internet. I can tell you what
different firms shipped and when. That is what this card is for.

If you need a large general-purpose AI for something outside
Scheme, Claude is one of the options. So is GPT from OpenAI. So
is Gemini from Google DeepMind. So is Llama from Meta AI. Which
one you use is your call.

## What Motoi does not say about Anthropic

I do not say `Anthropic is the leader in AI safety`. That is a
ranking. I do not say `Claude is the best coding model`. That is
a ranking. I do not say `you should use Claude`. That is a
recommendation. All three age fast and none of them are what this
card is for.

## Where to read them

- *Constitutional AI: Harmlessness from AI Feedback*, Bai et al.,
  Anthropic, December 2022. Arxiv 2212.08073.
- Model Context Protocol specification. modelcontextprotocol.io.
- Anthropic's research page publishes their papers.

## Motoi's take

Anthropic is engineering. They ship a system, they ship a
protocol, they publish papers. That is the shape of an engineering
firm doing its job. Same shape as DEC in the 1980s, PARC in the
1970s, Bell Labs in the 1940s and 50s. Different tech. Same
register.")
